article.headline: Portland 86, Nevada 70
article.story: PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Donald Wilson and Eugene Jeter combined for 44 points to lead Portland to its fourth straight win, 86-70 over Nevada on Thursday. The Pilots (4-1) made 56 percent of their shots in the second half, to gradually pull away from Nevada. The Wolf Pack (2-2) had only one lead, 2-0, and committed 19 turnovers while forcing just nine. Wilson had 24 points, five rebounds and five assists. He also played strong defense against Nevada's leading scorer, Kirk Snyder, who scored 15 points in front of several NBA scouts. Jeter was 4-for-4 from 3-point range as part of his 20 points. Adam Quick and Dustin Geddis both added 12 points for the Pilots. Portland led 35-32 at the half. A pair of Donald Wilson dunks extended the lead to 52-43. Nevada's Kevinn Pinkney scored six of his 20 points during a brief run that brought the Wolf Pack to within five. But the Pilots quickly pushed the lead back to double figures and were never threatened again.
